==Chinese==

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|屮|一|ls=ic|t1=bud|t2=ground}} – [[sprouting]] from the ground. A conservative version is [[𤯓]], which is unrelated to [[㞷]] ([[匩]] > [[匡]]) and [[𡴀]] > [[丰]].

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|alt=𤯓}}
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*sreŋ||to live; to be alive; to give birth; raw; green}}. Cognate with {{cog|my|ရှင်||tr=hrang|to live; alive}}, {{cog|lus|hring||to bear; to bring forth; to give birth to; green}}.

{{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} proposes that {{cog|sit-pro||*sriŋ}} is derived from the root {{m|sit-pro|*sri||to exist}} (whence possibly Chinese {{och-l|體|gloss=body; shape; form}}) + {{m|sit-pro|*-ŋ|pos=terminative suffix}}.

Both level tone and falling tone readings are found in Middle Chinese, but the latter has since been lost and is merged into the level-tone reading in modern dialects.

Related to {{och-l|青|gloss=blue-green}}, {{och-l|蒼|gloss=dark blue; deep green}}.

Derivatives: {{och-l|性|gloss=nature; character; personality; quality}}, {{och-l|姓|gloss=family name}}.

Pronunciation in Early Middle Chinese is ''*sraeng'', but it comes from an earlier ''*srjaeng'', as seen in Wang Renxu's edition of the Qieyun.

